, why such stories often remain sealed up within a culture, unknown to outsiders. Labeling this phenomenon "insider cultural knowledge," Cohen investigates the relationship between past story and present reality. He inquires why at certain moments in their collective lives peoples are especially drawn to narratives from the distant past that resonate strongly with their current circumstances, and why the Chinese have returned over and over to a story from twenty-five centuries ago. In this imaginative stitching of story to history, Cohen reveals how the shared narratives of a community help to define its culture and illuminate its history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh  a20th century chinese history.  a5th century chinese history.  aantiquity.  abai hua.  achiang kai shek.  achina.  achinese culture.  achinese history.  acollective memory.  acrisis and response.  across cultural perspectives.  acultural narratives.  acultural studies.  afolklore.  afolktales.  ahistory.  ahope.  ainsider cultural knowledge.  ainspiration.  aking goujian.  alate qing years.  anational humiliation.  anobility.  apast story.  apolitical allegory.  apolitical.  apresent reality.  aprivatizing china.  arepublican years.  aroyalty.  ataiwan.  awoxin changdan fever.  axiao jun.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025579140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094239440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520942394423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520942394/original  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backl